# SEO Optimizer Rules

Follow `docs/guidelines/SEO.md` for the full operational guide. These rules apply whenever adding or changing routes, metadata, or crawler-facing files in `apps/web`.

## Central configuration

- Keep site-wide SEO constants in `apps/web/app/shared/values.ts`: `baseUrl`, `appTitle`, `appTitleTemplate`, `appDescription`.
- Never hardcode production URLs in `robots.ts`, `sitemap.ts`, or page metadata — import from `values.ts`.
- Root layout (`apps/web/app/layout.tsx`) owns `metadataBase`, default `title`, and `description`. Page-level metadata only overrides what differs.

## File-based metadata assets

Place Next.js [file-based metadata](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/metadata) under `apps/web/app/`:

| File | Purpose |
| ---- | ------- |
| `favicon.ico` | Browser tab icon |
| `icon.svg` | Scalable app icon |
| `apple-icon.png` | iOS home-screen icon |
| `opengraph-image.png` | Default Open Graph / social preview image |

Do not duplicate these in `public/` unless a non-App-Router consumer requires it.

## Crawler route policy

Routes fall into two classes. **Never** put forbidden routes in `sitemap.ts`.

### Public (indexable)

Marketing and entry pages intended for search discovery:

- `/`
- `/about`
- `/contact`
- `/login`
- `/signup`

New public marketing pages must be added to `sitemap.ts` with an appropriate `changeFrequency` and `priority`.

### Forbidden (no indexing)

Authenticated, role-restricted, or internal routes must stay out of search results:

- `/dashboard` — authenticated hub
- `/admin`, `/manager`, `/member` — role dashboards
- `/instruments` — internal data example
- `/files` — authenticated upload utility
- Any future route behind auth, RBAC, or intended for signed-in users only
- URLs with query strings (`/*?*` — filter/search/session state)

When adding a forbidden route, apply **both** defenses:

1. **`robots.ts`** — add a `disallow` entry for the path prefix.
2. **Route layout metadata** — export `robots: { index: false, follow: false }` in the route's `layout.tsx` (preferred) or `page.tsx` if no layout exists.

Example (`apps/web/app/dashboard/layout.tsx`):

```typescript
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Dashboard',
  robots: { index: false, follow: false },
};
```

`robots.txt` alone is not sufficient — page-level `robots` metadata is the authoritative signal when content is accidentally linked externally.

## `robots.ts` and `sitemap.ts`

- `apps/web/app/robots.ts` — `allow: '/'`, `disallow` all forbidden prefixes, reference `${baseUrl}/sitemap.xml`.
- `apps/web/app/sitemap.ts` — only public routes; use `baseUrl` from `values.ts`.
- Keep `disallow` paths in `robots.ts` synchronized with the forbidden-route list above and any new protected routes.

## Page metadata conventions

- Use the root `title.template` (`%s | Jira Teams`) — set only the segment in child pages: `title: 'About'`.
- Public pages may add `description`, `openGraph`, and `twitter` overrides when the default root description is insufficient.
- Do not set `robots: { index: true }` on forbidden routes.
- Do not use `noindex` on public marketing pages unless there is an explicit product reason.

## Delivery checklist

- [ ] Route classified as public or forbidden.
- [ ] Forbidden routes: `disallow` in `robots.ts` + `robots: { index: false, follow: false }` in layout/page metadata.
- [ ] Public routes: entry in `sitemap.ts` when appropriate.
- [ ] Titles and descriptions use `values.ts` constants where shared.
- [ ] No secrets or user-specific data in metadata or OG images.
- [ ] Verify locally: `/robots.txt` and `/sitemap.xml` reflect changes.
